<P>Note, The doubtful forms of power, liberty, &amp;c. are expre&s;&s;ed by the pre&s;ent ten&s;e ab&s;olute of the potential mode; as, "if I may, can," &amp;c. and the hypothetical forms, by the conditional ten&s;es of the &s;ame mode; as, "if I might," &amp;c.</P>
<P>It may be further remarked, that the definite ten&s;es of verbs are all formed by adding the par|ticiple in <HI>ing,</HI> to the foregoing verb in all its variations.</P>
<P><PB N="50" REF="018871_0049_0FA8216253EA7320">The indicative form of the future is al&s;o very often u&s;ed with a preceding conjunction; as, "if I &s;hall," &amp;c.</P>
