<P>The interrogation and exclamation points are &s;uf|ficiently explained by their names: they are inde|terminate as to their quantity or time, and may be equivalent in that re&s;pect to a &s;emicolon, a colon, or a period, as the &s;en&s;e requires. They mark an ele|vation of the voice.</P>
<P><PB N="139" REF="018871_0138_0FA821015E8DEE10">The par<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">nt<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">e&s;is inclo&s;es in the body of a &s;entence a member me<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">t<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">d into it, which is neither nece&s;&s;a|ry to the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">en<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> nor at all affects the con&s;truction. It makes a moderate depre&s;&s;ion of the vo<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">, with a pau&s;e greater than a comma.</P>
